<br>
Kalial sighed again.  His father Jorloc being a high priest of Innoruuk would no doubt have demanded one of two things from his only son, become a Priest of Hate or join the ranks of the Necromancers.  Sure, there were those who did other things with their fate.  They channeled the elements, or summoned great magic.  They became masters of illusion and glamour.  But those who did paid a high price, they become the Outcasts, the shunned.  Kalial wondered often what their society might do to the Outcasts if they were not all Innoruuk's children and under the iron law of the church.  He also wondered if his father would kill him outright for his defiance.<br>
<br>
Kalial had no intention of becoming a priest or a bonecaster.  Instead, he had been drawn into the dark forbidding world of the Ebon Hand.  Assassins of the Ebon Hand were nigh invisible to the rest of Dark Elf society.  They were never talked of, taught about or mentioned even in passing.  A passing glance toward one of their numbers seemed to flow right around them, leaving them unseen and unnoticed.<br>
<br>
It was this very allure of secrecy that drove him to risk everything by telling his father that he planned to approach the guild master of the Ebon Hall and ask them to consider him for guilding.  And he would, live or die by Innoruuk!<br>
<br>
Stretching to his full height of five and a half feet, he straightened the tunic on his slender but wiry frame and brushed the tail of snow-driven hair over his shoulder, readying himself for battle.  Pushing the black oak door open with one palm, he stalked into the main living chamber and only the startled look on his father's face revealed that he had been sneaking without thinking about it and surprised him.<br>
<br>
Jorloc closed the dusty tome he had been browsing and covered his surprise with a half-sneer, &quot;What is it boy?  Are you here to have me take you to the Temple already?  Will you serve the will of Innoruuk?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kalial steeled himself and took a half step forward.<br>
