<br>
His father's reaction was hardly what he expected.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh?  I see...” Jorloc replied as if is son has mentioned it was raining outside and turned his back on his son.    <br>
<br>
Kalial's face was twisting into a mask of confusion as the silence stretched a few moments when something whistled past his head with tremendous force causing him to pitch to his left in avoidance.  As he rolled back up to his feet with cat-like grace, a violent crash signified the destruction of a bookcase somewhere behind him and to his right.<br>
<br>
&quot;Father!” Kalial cried as he stared in stunned silence at the blinding speed with which the mace had nearly splintered his skull.  Almost too late he picked up the muted chanting coming from across the room and rushed to close the distance and perhaps distract the High Priest from reducing him to a dark stain on his father's carpet.<br>
<br>
Throwing a left hook into Jorloc's exposed side produced a small but satisfying grunt from him, however the High Priest continued his chanting with tears of pain welling in his eyes.  The air became charged and the small hairs on the nape of Kalial's neck warned that another failed attempt to interrupt this spell might prove fatal.  Quickly sliding his dagger out and spinning it in mid-stroke he hammered the side of Jorloc's lower skull, near the spine with his hilt.  Jorloc stopped chanting and pitched himself forward into a roll.  His recovery was unsteady but now he was on the defensive and Kalial did not pursue but simply stood coiled and ready to strike again.<br>
<br>
The two men stared at one another for what seemed an eternity until Jorloc straightened his stance and rubbed his neck with a rueful smile.<br>
<br>
&quot;At least your serious about this boy.  Perhaps the will of Innoruuk has revealed you are ready to assist us in another capacity.&quot;  He began chanting what Kalial recognized as a healing spell and the younger elf relaxed a bit.  A blue glow momentarily enveloped the priest and with a last check his hand dropped away from his neck.<br>
<br>
Kalial was almost afraid to ask.  &quot;What do you mean father?  That I will not be killed for disobeying you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ha!  If I had wanted a simpering fool for a child I would have kidnapped a high-elven maid and raised myself a daughter!  Every elf makes his own fate with Innoruuk or it crushes him under its heel.  You've made your decision and stood by it.  Besides...&quot; he added, &quot;There is something the church needs from one who passes the tests of the Ebon Hand.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The church needing the Ebon Hand?  It must be serious...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Don't be a fool boy of course it is!&quot; Jorloc snapped.  &quot;Now sit down and silence your tongue for a moment, I have a history lesson for you.  Attend me.&quot;<br>
