<br>
He then poured another glass of the dark liquid and offered it to Kalial who gladly took it and quaffed the wine in a couple draughts.<br>
<br>
“This is why you must pass the tests and gain the training of the Ebon Hand.  Only with their expertise in stealth and subterfuge could you hope to infiltrate this new kingdom and learn what we desperately need to know.”  Cold eyes burned the message home and for some odd reason, Kalial no longer felt as fulfilled as he had imagined this undertaking would make him.  “I have a few things that might aid you in this…”  Standing from the small wooden bench, he walked over to another dusty bookshelf and pressing his hand against something that Kalial couldn’t see.  A hidden compartment swung open and revealed a dusty burlap sack, securely tied shut.  Hefting the bag over one shoulder, Jorloc once again closed the small door and it vanished before his son’s eyes, not even its outline was discernable.  Jorloc walked back to the bench at sat, then passed the sack to Kalial.<br>
<br>
“This sack lightens the load inside, making the work of hauling things much easier.  Inside you will find a special weapon, a mystic jerkin and an Idol of Hate I crafted during the last lunar eclipse.”  Jorloc half-smiled at his son and Kalial almost imagined that the man was actually proud of him.  <br>
<br>
Opening the sack, Kalial withdrew a light but wicked-looking dagger that seemed have been lovingly carved from a single length of bone.  Its blade was slightly curved and the edge had supple teeth along it.  An almost palpable evil radiated from the blade and it was cold to the touch.  Kalial gave a sharp intake of breath at being honored with such a deadly weapon.  Sliding it carefully into his sheath, he rummaged in the bag and extracted an odd-looking leather-like tunic.  Kalial could not decide if it was indeed leather, or some kind of lacquered material.  Upon closer inspection, he deduced that the entire piece was composed of interwoven tree-bark and giant, hardened leaves.<br>
<br>
“Father, isn’t this elven make?  By those damnable wild elves?” Kalial asked.<br>
<br>
“Yes.  How fitting that you will use it to help destroy them.”  Jorloc admonished Kalial’s hesitance, “Oh, don’t worry boy.  It’s not intelligent and doesn’t concern itself with motives.  It will serve the will of Innoruuk well.”<br>
<br>
Slipping on the armor, the young dark-elf felt a swell of power and strength ripple through his body.  Knocking his fist against the chest plate, he felt that even Adamantite arrows may not penetrate such sturdy material.  Among some carefully wrapped loaves of black bread and bricks of white cheese, Kalial found a sinister looking icon of hate and loathing.  Looking like what he could only think as an imp, the small silver statuette produced a slow burning anger and hate as he gazed upon it.  Giving himself a small shake, he placed it back into the sack and secured it once again.<br>
<br>
“You honor me father, with treasures beyond measure.  I shall do as you ask and learn from the Ebon Mask.  Then I will seek to study in their secret sub-sect, the Ebon Hand.”  Kalial stood and waited to be dismissed.<br>
<br>
“Very well boy.  I expect results.  The council may well exterminate our entire family if we fail, so do not fail.”<br>
<br>
With that, Kalial Fay’Ral strode from his father’s library on a path of mystery and danger.<br>
